  "conversation_comments": [
    {
      "id": "IC_kwDOSqVa0c8AAAABKYOMRw",
      "body": "## Audit review (read-only pass \u2014 no changes)\n\n- **[Medium]** `internal/gitutil/git.go:296-298` \u2014 classification is still a locale-fragile stderr string-match; confirmed live (git 2.54.0, `LC_ALL=fr_FR.UTF-8 git show HEAD:missing.go` \u2192 `fatal : le chemin 'missing.go' n'existe pas dans 'HEAD'`), which matches none of `\"exists on disk, but not in\"` / `\"does not exist\"` / `\"not found\"`. A genuinely-absent file under a non-English git locale now returns a hard error instead of `(\"\", false, nil)`. This is **not a regression** \u2014 the old code was equally fragile for any filename not containing the accidental `\"Path\"` substring \u2014 so it doesn't block this PR, but it's exactly the gap Pass A/B asks about and it's a live, reproducible miss, not theoretical. Worth a follow-up: pin `cmd.Env` to `LC_ALL=C`/`LANG=C` on the git subprocess (cheap, deterministic), or use an exit-code-based existence check (e.g. `git cat-file -e rev:path`) instead of stderr text matching.\n\n- **[Medium]** `internal/sem/analyze.go:33,39` and `internal/sem/dependents.go:65` (not touched by this PR, but directly affected by it) \u2014 these callers do `if err != nil { return Result{}/nil, err }` on `ShowFile`. Before this fix, a real error on a `\"Path\"`-containing filename was silently swallowed as absent \u2014 wrong for that one file, but the batch continued. After this fix, that same error now aborts the *entire* `AnalyzeGitRange` call / the *entire* `buildReferenceIndex` build (discarding every delta/reference already collected for every other file in the commit range or repo). `analyze.go` already has a graceful-degradation convention a few lines below (a hard parse failure becomes a `result.Warnings` entry + `continue`, not an abort) \u2014 worth confirming whether a transient/single-file `ShowFile` failure (flaky IO, a tight `ctx` deadline hit deep in a large loop) deserves the same per-file isolation rather than an all-or-nothing hard fail. Not a bug in this diff's own two files, but a real widening of blast radius caused by it, worth a deliberate call.\n\n- **[Low/Nit]** `internal/gitutil/git.go:298` \u2014 I could not get the `\"not found\"` arm to fire on real git 2.54.0 for any `ShowFile`-relevant failure (bad rev, missing path, uncommitted-but-on-disk path, corrupted/missing blob object, submodule gitlink path, blob-treated-as-tree traversal) \u2014 all land on `\"does not exist\"` / `\"exists on disk, but not in\"` or correctly propagate as real errors. May be a defensive catch for an older/different git message I didn't reproduce, but it's untested and possibly dead, in the same spirit as the redundant `\"Path\"` clause this PR just removed. `(speculative \u2014 did not exhaustively test across git versions)`\n\n**Solid:**\n- Root cause is correctly diagnosed and fixed exactly as scoped: classification now sees git's own `stderr` only, never the wrapped `run()` message that echoes `rev+\":\"+path` \u2014 verified this closes the reported hole (bad rev on `src/PathHelper.go` no longer swallowed).\n- `run()`'s refactor onto `runWithStderr` is byte-for-byte behavior-preserving (same `TrimSpace`, same fallback-to-`err.Error()`, identical wrapped message format) for all 9 other call sites \u2014 zero blast radius there.\n- Regression test directly encodes the bug report (bad-rev-on-Path-filename, genuinely-missing-file, existing-file) and CI is green on macOS/Linux/Windows for build+test+lint. Diff matches the stated +69/-14 with no hidden hunks.\n\n**Overall:** Correct, minimal, well-tested fix for the reported bug \u2014 safe to merge. The two Medium items (residual locale-fragility, widened failure blast radius in two downstream callers) are pre-existing/consequential rather than introduced-and-broken, and worth tracking as follow-ups rather than blocking this PR.\n",
